Dullfiina, you'll be surprised to notice, as I did, that many Americans will make more mistakes than many foreigners, as they seem to pay less attention to their language. The fact the U.S. has the national practice of spelling bees, and are so very proud of it, never ceased to amaze me. I don't think I heard of something like that in any other country.<br>
<br>
Yeah, I too cringe at inappropriate usage, and misspellings. No, I'm not a native English speaker, but I studied <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
I pay attention to my written words, and while I'm not infallible, and make the occasional misspeling or grammatical error, I think I'm better than most. It's mostly a matter of attention and opinion - do I care what my words look like, and do I want others to read and understand them, or am I only interested in getting them out of my system? I think words are a means of communications, and as such, I use them to convey my thoughts and ideas to others. Hence I'm inherently interested in said others understanding what I had to say, and I make an effort for them to be able to.<br>
<br>
As for 'teh', I thought of is as a simple mistype as well, in the beginning. I think it evolved further, and is now used as a greater form of 'the' - maybe something like 'THE'.  *grin* <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=95331" target="_new">
